Stage B recipe (per remaining family: colr, path, tt_hinted_text,
autohint, subpixel, text_sample, linear_resolve)
----------------------------------------------------------------
1. Port the family's fragment body from src/snail/shader/glsl/ into a new
   module (math 1:1; textures/uniform scalars as parameters). Reuse
   coverage_common/color_common/text_coverage/vertex.
2. Add entries to a families/<name>.slang following families/text.slang's
   binding pattern (three target flavors; layer-info tex = binding 2,
   image array = binding 3 for paint-record families).
3. Extend build/slang_shaders.zig's matrix (same flags; via-glsl for any
   naga-bound stage with loops).
4. Wire behind the existing per-family switch points: contract.zig recipe
   (Vulkan), gl shaders.zig + loadNativeTextProgramState-style loader
   (GL/GLES), minimal_wgpu Pipelines.init (WGSL).
5. Gate: regenerate baselines from the unmodified tree first, then require
   AE 0 (GL/GLES) and the existing tolerance (Vulkan/wgpu); run the
   validation-layer sweep and diff message counts.
   Family-specific watchpoints: subpixel needs dual-source outputs
   ([[vk::location(0)]] index 0/1 — check slangc drops the index qualifier
   like the ingestion path did, and that glBindFragDataLocationIndexed
   still applies on the GL side); autohint has a texture read in the
   VERTEX stage (fetch through a via-glsl-compatible path — no spirv_asm
   in that stage; its vertex index must come from another route, e.g.
   compile the autohint vertex leg direct only if it stays loop-free);
   paint-record families read u_layer_tex/u_image_tex with SAMPLING
   (not just Load) — declare SamplerState and check the split-sampler
   binding contract on WGSL (group 1) and the GL combined-sampler names.

SPIRV-Cross GL legs — spike notes (2026-07-21, branch slang-cutover)
====================================================================
The glsl330/gles300 legs now go slangc direct SPIR-V → SPIRV-Cross
(spirv-cross from nixpkgs, added to shell.nix); naga is out of gen-shaders
entirely (it remains only in the legacy wgsl_shaders catalog path). Full
gate suite green and EVERY image gate byte-identical (AE=0) to the clean
156636c baselines: demo{cpu,gl,gles30}, banner{gl,gles30}, minimal-gl,
game-{gl33,gl44,gles30}, iso/seam/gamma probe images, and backend-compare
reproduces the baseline mismatch count exactly (4465/96000, outliers 0).

Per-dialect flags (source of truth: build/slang_shaders.zig):
  glsl330  spirv-cross <spv> --version 330 --no-420pack-extension
  gles300  spirv-cross <spv> --version 300 --es, then
           build/glsl_patch_es_highp.zig (default precision mediump→highp;
           SPIRV-Cross only qualifies globals, locals inherit the default)
  both     --rename-interface-variable {out|in} L snail_ioL for L=0..14
           (vert renames "out", frag renames "in"; unknown locations are
           ignored). Load-bearing: GLSL <4.10 links varyings BY NAME and
           the two stages' SPIR-V carry different OpNames
           (entryPointParam_vertexMain_* vs input_*).

Loader contract changes (snail.shader.slang_generated):
  - ONE uniform block name for both stages: SnailPushConstants_std140
    (identical definition in vert+frag → the GL linker merges them; the
    two-name lookup and the via-vertex fallback are gone).
  - Combined samplers: SPIRV_Cross_Combined<tex>SPIRV_Cross_DummySampler
    for Load-only textures, SPIRV_Cross_Combined<tex><sampler> for real
    Sample sites. u_image_tex is both Loaded and Sampled, so TWO uniforms
    exist for it — the loaders bind both to the image unit. The autohint
    vertex layer read now shares the fragment's combined-sampler name
    (one uniform after linking; the _vs/_fs naming split is gone).
  - Artifacts are "#version 330" (no "core" suffix) and roughly half the
    naga emission's size (generated/ diff: −33.8k/+18.3k lines).

Traps DEAD with SPIRV-Cross:
  2.  via-glsl for loop stages: SPIRV-Cross structurizes slang's direct
      SPIR-V loops correctly (all loop-bearing families gate-exact). Every
      GL leg is direct now; a stage can have loops AND spirv_asm.
  10. spirv-opt ADCE between compile and translate: not needed (SPIRV-Cross
      accepts the -O0 modules naga rejected, arrayed GetDimensions incl.).
  13. base-vertex patch: dead. With every leg direct, the autohint vertex
      uses the spirv_asm raw-VertexIndex load like all other families
      (families/autohint.slang #if is now WGSL-vs-rest) and SPIRV-Cross
      emits plain gl_VertexID. Do NOT reintroduce SV_VertexID on a GL leg:
      BaseVertex is a hard error in SPIRV-Cross's ES backend ("BaseVertex
      not supported in ES profile") and an ARB_shader_draw_parameters
      dependency on the 330 leg. build/glsl_patch_base_vertex.zig is
      unused (kept on disk for history).
  15. (GL half) spv_patch_dual_source: dead. SPIRV-Cross emits
      `layout(location = 0, index = 1)` on the blend output straight from
      the [[vk::index(1)]] decoration and leaves index-0 implicit (the GL
      default) — no explicit Index-0 patch, no
      glBindFragDataLocationIndexed. The WGSL half (no @blend_src at
      declaration level) stands, but see the interop spike below: a valid
      dual-source WGSL artifact is now generated via __requirePrelude.
  17. (desktop half) texel-buffer rejection: dead. text_sample now has a
      glsl330 artifact — plain `uniform usamplerBuffer
      u_snail_text_records` + SnailTextSampleParams_std140 — which
      glslangValidator accepts as-is. The GLES half of 17 STANDS in
      stronger form: texel buffers do not exist in ES 3.0 at any extension
      level (SPIRV-Cross emits GL_EXT_texture_buffer, but that extension
      requires ES 3.1 — the output only validates rewritten to `#version
      310 es`), so text_sample stays no_gles and the R32UI interface
      remains the ES 3.0 answer.

Traps SURVIVING:
  1.  SV_VertexID lowering (see 13 above — now enforced by the ES leg).
  11. cubic-solver fusion: SURVIVES the translator swap, confirming it is
      a Mesa code-shape sensitivity, not a naga emission artifact. Without
      the patch: demo-gl/gles30 AE=6/96000, banner-gl/gles30 AE=46/921600,
      every diff 1 LSB (max_channel_delta=1), all in high-contrast AA edge
      neighborhoods on cubic path panels; backend-compare drifts 4465→4462.
      build/glsl_patch_cubic_solver.zig needed a one-line relax (SPIRV-Cross
      keeps the un-mangled `solveMonotonicCubicRoot(` OpName; naga added
      `_` + counter) and restores AE=0.
  9.  gl_o0 is KEPT but measured NOT load-bearing anymore: with default -O
      on every GL leg (cubic patch on) all nine screenshot gates were
      still AE=0 — the direct-SPIR-V leg preserves the constant divisions
      that the via-glsl (glslang) leg strength-reduced, and artifacts
      shrink further. Candidate merge-time simplification: drop gl_o0,
      which also collapses the painted GL vertex back into text.vert
      (identical flags → identical compile) and kills gl_only. Left in
      place for this spike to keep the shipped config the fully
      suite-validated one. The Vulkan/WGSL default-O pinning of trap 9 is
      untouched (their baselines are unchanged — no spirv/wgsl artifact
      diffs).

New tool: build/glsl_patch_es_highp.zig (ES default-precision promotion).
Real-ES caveat: gates run on Mesa (fp32 regardless); on real ES hardware
the highp default is required for the coverage math and is now explicit.

Recommendation: KEEP. One translator (SPIRV-Cross) instead of naga +
glslang-via-glsl + ADCE + two SPIR-V/GLSL patch tools, one leg shape for
all stages, byte-exact gates without re-baselining, and the text_sample
desktop GL artifact naga could not produce. Re-baselining is NOT required
at merge (AE=0 everywhere); if gl_o0 is dropped later, re-run the full
suite (only the screenshot gates were checked under default -O).

Slang-native interop spike (2026-07-21, a1-04 mechanisms vs patch tools)
========================================================================
Question: can `__target_switch` / `__intrinsic_asm` / `__requirePrelude` /
spirv_asm replace the external patch tools? One structural fact decides
the two GL candidates: since the SPIRV-Cross cutover, slangc NEVER emits
the final GL text. The GL legs are `-target spirv`, so `case glsl:` does
not even fire (verified: a glsl-case intrinsic is ignored on the direct
leg, taken on -emit-spirv-via-glsl), and everything injected at slangc's
GLSL emission is immediately compiled by glslang and re-emitted by
SPIRV-Cross in SPIRV-Cross's own shape. In-source text control over the
artifact is impossible by construction.

1. Cubic-solver fusion pin (glsl_patch_cubic_solver): FAILED, tool KEPT.
   Mechanism tried: `__target_switch { case glsl: __requirePrelude(<the
   composed spec text, raw string>) + __intrinsic_asm forwarding call }`
   with the colr/path GL legs switched to -emit-spirv-via-glsl (compiles
   clean; slangc 2026.5.2 accepts prelude+intrinsic in a case, raw R"()"
   strings included). Two independent kills:
   a) The injected composed text does NOT survive: glslang→SPIRV-Cross
      re-emits it with short-circuit `&&`/`||` lowered to branch
      temporaries and reprinted literals — the artifact carries a THIRD
      solver shape, not the spec text, defeating the tool's purpose.
   b) The via-glsl leg breaks the loader name contract wholesale: uniform
      block `SnailPushConstants_std140` → `block_SnailPushConstants_0`,
      samplers gain slang's `_0` mangling
      (`SPIRV_Cross_Combinedu_curve_tex_0SPIRV_Cross_DummySampler`) —
      nothing binds. Gate: demo-gl/gles30, banner-gl/gles30, game-*
      grossly broken (backend-compare 4465→81871/96000, max_delta 224).
      Reverted; the patch tool remains the only way to pin the artifact
      text.

2. ES highp default (glsl_patch_es_highp): FAILED, tool KEPT. Same
   structural reason: the `precision mediump float;` line is emitted by
   SPIRV-Cross itself; no slangc-side mechanism reaches it, and GLSL
   default-precision is not representable in SPIR-V (nothing spirv_asm
   could pin). The C++ API has the knob
   (CompilerGLSL::Options::fragment.default_float_precision) but the
   spirv-cross CLI at 1.4.341.0 does not expose it (verified against
   --help and by probing flag spellings). Equivalent-native alternative
   would be a tiny C++ shim over the API — a bigger tool, not a deletion.

3. WGSL dual-source (subpixel no_wgsl): ACHIEVED — no_wgsl is OFF and
   generated/wgsl/text_subpixel.frag.wgsl now exists and validates in
   naga (wgpu-utils 29.0.1 accepts `enable dual_source_blending` +
   `@blend_src`). Mechanism: declaration-level is still impossible (the
   WGSL backend renumbers the [[vk::index(1)]] output to @location(1) —
   silently wrong MRT semantics, no @blend_src anywhere in libslang), but
   `__target_switch { case wgsl: __requirePrelude(...) }` injects raw
   WGSL at the very TOP of the module — a legal position for both the
   `enable` directive and a hand-written second entry point
   (`fragmentDualMain`), because WGSL module-scope declarations are
   order-independent, so the prelude entry can call the slang-emitted
   body helper defined later. The prelude entry re-declares its own
   varyings but must reference slang's MANGLED names
   (snailSubpixelFragment_0, SubpixelVaryings_0.color_2, u_curve_tex_0,
   pc_0.layer_base_0, ...): stable per module content, NOT an API
   contract — any edit to the family or its imports can renumber them
   (gen-shaders + naga validation is the tripwire). A reachability
   anchor call in fragmentMain keeps the prelude live. The plain
   fragmentMain (MRT 0/1) coexists in the artifact; a dual-source
   consumer must select entry `fragmentDualMain`. NOTHING is wired
   (minimal_wgpu keeps the old catalog); an upstream slang issue for
   real [[vk::index]]→@blend_src support is still the right ask.

Double-underscore stability caveat: `__target_switch`, `__intrinsic_asm`,
`__requirePrelude`, and the R"()" raw strings are the UNDOCUMENTED-tier
compiler-internal surface (a1-04 explicitly reserves the right to break
them); the subpixel WGSL artifact additionally depends on slang's name
mangling. Treat candidate 3 as a regeneration-time convenience guarded by
naga validation, not a stable contract.

